    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What are cyclical stocks?</summary>
        <p>Cyclical stocks are equities of companies whose performance is highly correlated with the overall economy. They thrive in expansions and struggle in recessions.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are some examples of cyclical stocks?</summary>
        <p>Examples include automakers, airlines, hotels, restaurants, and luxury goods manufacturers.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How are cyclical stocks different from defensive stocks?</summary>
        <p>Defensive stocks (like utilities and consumer staples) remain relatively stable regardless of economic conditions, whereas cyclical stocks fluctuate with the economy.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>When is the best time to buy cyclical stocks?</summary>
        <p>Investors often look to buy cyclical stocks at the bottom of an economic cycle when prices are low and sell them near the peak when the economy is booming.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Are cyclical stocks risky?</summary>
        <p>They carry higher volatility than defensive stocks because their revenues can drop significantly during economic downturns.</p>
      </details>
